    <p>the surface is dying.</p>
    <p>the heat killed your camp three days ago. the others didn't make it.</p>
    <p>you walked. three days. no water. no shade. no one. just cracked earth and yellow sky filled with dust.</p>
    <p>you stopped sweating on the second day. you kept walking because stopping meant lying down. and lying down meant not getting up.</p>
    <p>on the third day you saw a hole in the ground. dark and still. you went towards it because there was nothing else.</p>
    <p>the edge crumbled under your weight. you fell for a long time.</p>

    <p>when you wake someone is sitting near you in the shade. his name is Horris. you can tell by the way the dust has settled around him that he has been here a while. he tosses you an old miner's headlamp. he says it gets dark down there. he says he's watched a lot of people go down. not many come back. he settles back against the wall. he says he's happy here. he likes the quiet.</p>

    <p>you think one thing, clearly: i am not dying here.</p>

    <h2>the dust · 1 — 30</h2>
    <p>where you wake. Horris sits at depth one. the lip overhangs above you. there is no way up. dust drifts down from above. the rock is warm from the surface. something skitters somewhere overhead. probably nothing.</p>

    <h2>the stone · 31 — 80</h2>
    <p>the shaft narrows. the walls are smoother now — like something polished them, a long time ago. the dust from above doesn't reach this deep. the walls smell of old iron. you think you hear sounds. you can't be sure.</p>

    <h2>the writing · 81 — 120</h2>
    <p>inscriptions begin to appear on the walls. horrors. this place is not right. the wall remembers everyone. someone wrote a name here long ago. the wall is colder than it should be.</p>

    <h2>the damp · 121 — 160</h2>
    <p>your breath fogs. the rock is wet to the touch. water trickles somewhere out of sight. it's freezing cold. something drips, far above. the rock is slick. you slow down.</p>

    <h2>the quiet · 161 — 199</h2>
    <p>sound dies here. your words don't echo. your own breath sounds far away. this is not a place where things rest. you stop breathing for a moment to listen. the silence is wrong. the silence is full. something is paying attention.</p>

    <h2>the queen · 200</h2>
    <p>the shaft opens. there is a room below, not a tunnel. a strange light pulses from somewhere across the chamber. something biological. something alive in the walls.</p>
    <p>the floor is wet. it's not water. bones — scattered across the stone. picked clean. human. drag marks lead inward from every tunnel.</p>
    <p>this is where they bring them.</p>
    <p>she's at the center of the room. twice your size. her abdomen drags behind her, swollen with eggs that pulse beneath a membrane slick with fluid. her head turns toward you. hundreds of black lenses. every single one finds you at once.</p>
    <p>she doesn't need to be fast. everything that comes down here ends up in front of her eventually.</p>

    <h2>the ascent</h2>
    <p>if you kill her, the clicking falters and her body slumps. something deep below her shifts and goes still. beneath her, a sac. swollen. leaking something that hisses against the stone. wherever it touches, the rock blackens and gives.</p>
    <p>you take it. you climb.</p>
    <p>when you reach depth one the dust is undisturbed. the wall where Horris sat is bare. no prints. no lamp. no sign anyone was ever here.</p>
    <p>you crack the sac against the wall. it hisses. the rock blackens. gives. you climb. handhold by handhold. burning your way up.</p>
    <p>the surface. the heat hits you and you remember why you went down in the first place. but you are out.</p>

